</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Retroperitoneal lesions represent a broad, diverse collection of entities; when they contain fat, the differential diagnosis, which ranges from benign to fully malignant lesions, substantially narrows. Lipomas rarely occur in the retroperitoneum; thus, fat-containing lesions in this location should never be dismissed as lipoma. Pelvic lipomatosis is the overgrowth of histologically normal fat in the extraabdominal compartments of the pelvis along the perirectal and perivesicular spaces. Infants and young children develop lipoblastomas rather than liposarcomas, which occur in older patients. Liposarcomas typically occur in patients 50–70 years old and manifest in multiple subtypes, with the most common being well-differentiated liposarcoma. Liposarcomas are histologically and radiologically protean, with no one imaging feature specific across the spectrum of subtypes. Hibernoma is a rare benign soft-tissue tumor composed of brown fat. Because hibernomas contain varied portions of brown and white fat as well as lesser amounts of myxoid material and spindle cells, their imaging features vary considerably. Teratomas are neoplasms that originate in pluripotent cells—benign or malignant germ cells—that give rise to a wide spectrum of mature or immature tissues that are foreign to the location in which they arise and which demonstrate varying amounts of organ formation. Myelolipoma, a benign tumor composed of mature fat and interspersed hematopoietic elements that resemble bone marrow, typically originate in an otherwise normal adrenal gland. Angiomyolipoma is composed of varying admixtures of blood vessels, smooth muscle cells, and adipose tissue; any one or two of these elements may predominate. Although these fat-containing lesions have overlapping radiologic features, use of demographic and clinical data helps refine the diagnostic options and treatment.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291085203">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291085203">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g01a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1603" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  Pelvic lipomatosis in several middle-aged men. <b>(a)</b> Cystogram demonstrates the classic pear-shaped bladder. <b>(b)</b> Intravenous urogram shows bilateral hydroureter and hydronephrosis, caused by the medially deviated and segmentally narrowed distal ureters (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows straightening and elongation of the rectosigmoid colon (arrow). Remaining bowel loops are elevated out of the pelvis because of radiolucent fat. <b>(d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) scan obtained through the pelvis helps confirm the presence of symmetrically abundant fat that distorts both the urinary bladder (arrowhead) and rectum (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Venogram shows bilateral fusiform narrowing of the pelvic section of both femoral veins (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows unencapsulated, normal, benign, mature adipocytes, characteristic of lipomatosis. In each case shown here, the patient required surgical decompression.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g01b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1433" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  Pelvic lipomatosis in several middle-aged men. <b>(a)</b> Cystogram demonstrates the classic pear-shaped bladder. <b>(b)</b> Intravenous urogram shows bilateral hydroureter and hydronephrosis, caused by the medially deviated and segmentally narrowed distal ureters (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows straightening and elongation of the rectosigmoid colon (arrow). Remaining bowel loops are elevated out of the pelvis because of radiolucent fat. <b>(d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) scan obtained through the pelvis helps confirm the presence of symmetrically abundant fat that distorts both the urinary bladder (arrowhead) and rectum (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Venogram shows bilateral fusiform narrowing of the pelvic section of both femoral veins (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows unencapsulated, normal, benign, mature adipocytes, characteristic of lipomatosis. In each case shown here, the patient required surgical decompression.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g01c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1433" aria-labelledby="F1C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1c.</b>  Pelvic lipomatosis in several middle-aged men. <b>(a)</b> Cystogram demonstrates the classic pear-shaped bladder. <b>(b)</b> Intravenous urogram shows bilateral hydroureter and hydronephrosis, caused by the medially deviated and segmentally narrowed distal ureters (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows straightening and elongation of the rectosigmoid colon (arrow). Remaining bowel loops are elevated out of the pelvis because of radiolucent fat. <b>(d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) scan obtained through the pelvis helps confirm the presence of symmetrically abundant fat that distorts both the urinary bladder (arrowhead) and rectum (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Venogram shows bilateral fusiform narrowing of the pelvic section of both femoral veins (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows unencapsulated, normal, benign, mature adipocytes, characteristic of lipomatosis. In each case shown here, the patient required surgical decompression.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F1C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g01d.jpeg" height="1497" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1d.</b>  Pelvic lipomatosis in several middle-aged men. <b>(a)</b> Cystogram demonstrates the classic pear-shaped bladder. <b>(b)</b> Intravenous urogram shows bilateral hydroureter and hydronephrosis, caused by the medially deviated and segmentally narrowed distal ureters (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows straightening and elongation of the rectosigmoid colon (arrow). Remaining bowel loops are elevated out of the pelvis because of radiolucent fat. <b>(d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) scan obtained through the pelvis helps confirm the presence of symmetrically abundant fat that distorts both the urinary bladder (arrowhead) and rectum (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Venogram shows bilateral fusiform narrowing of the pelvic section of both femoral veins (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows unencapsulated, normal, benign, mature adipocytes, characteristic of lipomatosis. In each case shown here, the patient required surgical decompression.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F1D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g01e.jpeg" height="1692" width="1209" aria-labelledby="F1E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1e.</b>  Pelvic lipomatosis in several middle-aged men. <b>(a)</b> Cystogram demonstrates the classic pear-shaped bladder. <b>(b)</b> Intravenous urogram shows bilateral hydroureter and hydronephrosis, caused by the medially deviated and segmentally narrowed distal ureters (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows straightening and elongation of the rectosigmoid colon (arrow). Remaining bowel loops are elevated out of the pelvis because of radiolucent fat. <b>(d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) scan obtained through the pelvis helps confirm the presence of symmetrically abundant fat that distorts both the urinary bladder (arrowhead) and rectum (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Venogram shows bilateral fusiform narrowing of the pelvic section of both femoral veins (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows unencapsulated, normal, benign, mature adipocytes, characteristic of lipomatosis. In each case shown here, the patient required surgical decompression.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F1E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c01f.jpeg" height="914" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F1F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1f.</b>  Pelvic lipomatosis in several middle-aged men. <b>(a)</b> Cystogram demonstrates the classic pear-shaped bladder. <b>(b)</b> Intravenous urogram shows bilateral hydroureter and hydronephrosis, caused by the medially deviated and segmentally narrowed distal ureters (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Image from a barium enema study shows straightening and elongation of the rectosigmoid colon (arrow). Remaining bowel loops are elevated out of the pelvis because of radiolucent fat. <b>(d)</b> Axial computed tomographic (CT) scan obtained through the pelvis helps confirm the presence of symmetrically abundant fat that distorts both the urinary bladder (arrowhead) and rectum (arrow). <b>(e)</b> Venogram shows bilateral fusiform narrowing of the pelvic section of both femoral veins (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; hematoxylineosin [H-E] stain) shows unencapsulated, normal, benign, mature adipocytes, characteristic of lipomatosis. In each case shown here, the patient required surgical decompression.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F1F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g02a.jpeg" height="1322" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Pelvic lipoma in a 51-year-old woman with flank pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT scans demonstrate a fat-attenuation mass with a faintly visible capsule (arrows in <b>a</b>) that displaces the abdominal contents to the left of midline. Fibrous strands, septations, and solid components are notably absent. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen reveals a homogeneous, yellow, soft mass with a distinct capsular margin. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows adipocytes with small nuclei that vary in cell size and shape and histiocytes (arrowheads) that engulf the necrotic fat cells. These features should not be confused with atypical lipocytes found in liposarcoma and are indicative of benign lipoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g02b.jpeg" height="1322" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Pelvic lipoma in a 51-year-old woman with flank pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT scans demonstrate a fat-attenuation mass with a faintly visible capsule (arrows in <b>a</b>) that displaces the abdominal contents to the left of midline. Fibrous strands, septations, and solid components are notably absent. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen reveals a homogeneous, yellow, soft mass with a distinct capsular margin. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows adipocytes with small nuclei that vary in cell size and shape and histiocytes (arrowheads) that engulf the necrotic fat cells. These features should not be confused with atypical lipocytes found in liposarcoma and are indicative of benign lipoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c02c.jpeg" height="913" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F2C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2c.</b>  Pelvic lipoma in a 51-year-old woman with flank pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT scans demonstrate a fat-attenuation mass with a faintly visible capsule (arrows in <b>a</b>) that displaces the abdominal contents to the left of midline. Fibrous strands, septations, and solid components are notably absent. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen reveals a homogeneous, yellow, soft mass with a distinct capsular margin. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows adipocytes with small nuclei that vary in cell size and shape and histiocytes (arrowheads) that engulf the necrotic fat cells. These features should not be confused with atypical lipocytes found in liposarcoma and are indicative of benign lipoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F2C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c02d.jpeg" height="863" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F2D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2d.</b>  Pelvic lipoma in a 51-year-old woman with flank pain. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT scans demonstrate a fat-attenuation mass with a faintly visible capsule (arrows in <b>a</b>) that displaces the abdominal contents to the left of midline. Fibrous strands, septations, and solid components are notably absent. <b>(c)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen reveals a homogeneous, yellow, soft mass with a distinct capsular margin. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows adipocytes with small nuclei that vary in cell size and shape and histiocytes (arrowheads) that engulf the necrotic fat cells. These features should not be confused with atypical lipocytes found in liposarcoma and are indicative of benign lipoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F2D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c03a.jpeg" height="882" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Progressive maturation of lipoblastoma. Lipoblastoma and lipoblastomatosis are initially composed of sheets of immature lipoblasts (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) that undergo myxoid change (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b>) and eventually get replaced by adult type fat with retained thick fibrous septa (arrowheads in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c03b.jpeg" height="882" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Progressive maturation of lipoblastoma. Lipoblastoma and lipoblastomatosis are initially composed of sheets of immature lipoblasts (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) that undergo myxoid change (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b>) and eventually get replaced by adult type fat with retained thick fibrous septa (arrowheads in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c03c.jpeg" height="928" width="1228" aria-labelledby="F3C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3c.</b>  Progressive maturation of lipoblastoma. Lipoblastoma and lipoblastomatosis are initially composed of sheets of immature lipoblasts (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) that undergo myxoid change (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b>) and eventually get replaced by adult type fat with retained thick fibrous septa (arrowheads in <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F3C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c04a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1244" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Lipoblastoma in a healthy 4-month-old infant with an asymptomatic mass found at well-baby checkup. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative photograph shows the outlined borders of the palpable lesion. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT scan depicts a well-defined left retroperitoneal fatty mass with multiple thick septations (arrowheads), which are characteristic of lipoblastoma. <b>(c)</b> On a coronal T1-weighted MR image, the mass has slightly heterogeneous signal intensity and is generally less intense than the adjacent subcutaneous fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g04b.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Lipoblastoma in a healthy 4-month-old infant with an asymptomatic mass found at well-baby checkup. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative photograph shows the outlined borders of the palpable lesion. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT scan depicts a well-defined left retroperitoneal fatty mass with multiple thick septations (arrowheads), which are characteristic of lipoblastoma. <b>(c)</b> On a coronal T1-weighted MR image, the mass has slightly heterogeneous signal intensity and is generally less intense than the adjacent subcutaneous fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g04c.jpeg" height="1284" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  Lipoblastoma in a healthy 4-month-old infant with an asymptomatic mass found at well-baby checkup. <b>(a)</b> Preoperative photograph shows the outlined borders of the palpable lesion. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT scan depicts a well-defined left retroperitoneal fatty mass with multiple thick septations (arrowheads), which are characteristic of lipoblastoma. <b>(c)</b> On a coronal T1-weighted MR image, the mass has slightly heterogeneous signal intensity and is generally less intense than the adjacent subcutaneous fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g05a.jpeg" height="1311" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Lipoblastoma in a 1-year-old child with a 1-month history of abdominal distention, poor weight gain, and a palpable mass. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a large solid-appearing mass in the left side of the abdomen. <b>(b)</b> On an axial CT scan, the lesion appears laced with fat (arrows) but its overall attenuation more closely approximates that of the spinal canal. This “non-fat” attenuation suggests myxoid material, which is a recognized feature of lipoblastoma. <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows intermediate to high signal intensity throughout the lesion from the myxoid matrix and multiple septations (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Enhanced coronal T1-weighted MR image shows patchy enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g05b.jpeg" height="1207" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Lipoblastoma in a 1-year-old child with a 1-month history of abdominal distention, poor weight gain, and a palpable mass. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a large solid-appearing mass in the left side of the abdomen. <b>(b)</b> On an axial CT scan, the lesion appears laced with fat (arrows) but its overall attenuation more closely approximates that of the spinal canal. This “non-fat” attenuation suggests myxoid material, which is a recognized feature of lipoblastoma. <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows intermediate to high signal intensity throughout the lesion from the myxoid matrix and multiple septations (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Enhanced coronal T1-weighted MR image shows patchy enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g05c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1386" aria-labelledby="F5C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5c.</b>  Lipoblastoma in a 1-year-old child with a 1-month history of abdominal distention, poor weight gain, and a palpable mass. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a large solid-appearing mass in the left side of the abdomen. <b>(b)</b> On an axial CT scan, the lesion appears laced with fat (arrows) but its overall attenuation more closely approximates that of the spinal canal. This “non-fat” attenuation suggests myxoid material, which is a recognized feature of lipoblastoma. <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows intermediate to high signal intensity throughout the lesion from the myxoid matrix and multiple septations (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Enhanced coronal T1-weighted MR image shows patchy enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F5C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g05d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1386" aria-labelledby="F5D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5d.</b>  Lipoblastoma in a 1-year-old child with a 1-month history of abdominal distention, poor weight gain, and a palpable mass. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a large solid-appearing mass in the left side of the abdomen. <b>(b)</b> On an axial CT scan, the lesion appears laced with fat (arrows) but its overall attenuation more closely approximates that of the spinal canal. This “non-fat” attenuation suggests myxoid material, which is a recognized feature of lipoblastoma. <b>(c)</b> Coronal T2-weighted MR image shows intermediate to high signal intensity throughout the lesion from the myxoid matrix and multiple septations (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Enhanced coronal T1-weighted MR image shows patchy enhancement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F5D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g06a.jpeg" height="1111" width="1476" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma that underwent dedifferentiation. <b>(a)</b> CT scan obtained in 2003 shows a fatty mass (arrowheads) in the left perinephric space that was erroneously interpreted as a lipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan obtained 3 years later to evaluate urinary incontinence and increasing abdominal girth reveals a very large fatty mass that engulfs the left kidney and displaces the abdominal contents to the contralateral side. <b>(c)</b> A more cranial CT image shows multiple well-defined soft-tissue masses (arrowheads) embedded within the well-differentiated tumor. These masses are the hallmark of dedifferentiation. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the dedifferentiated liposarcoma clearly shows the central solid component (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a well-differentiated component immediately adjacent to a dedifferentiated component (<b>*</b>). The alipogenic dedifferentiated component can vary from low to high grade and must be large enough to fill a 10 × power field.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g06b.jpeg" height="1364" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma that underwent dedifferentiation. <b>(a)</b> CT scan obtained in 2003 shows a fatty mass (arrowheads) in the left perinephric space that was erroneously interpreted as a lipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan obtained 3 years later to evaluate urinary incontinence and increasing abdominal girth reveals a very large fatty mass that engulfs the left kidney and displaces the abdominal contents to the contralateral side. <b>(c)</b> A more cranial CT image shows multiple well-defined soft-tissue masses (arrowheads) embedded within the well-differentiated tumor. These masses are the hallmark of dedifferentiation. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the dedifferentiated liposarcoma clearly shows the central solid component (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a well-differentiated component immediately adjacent to a dedifferentiated component (<b>*</b>). The alipogenic dedifferentiated component can vary from low to high grade and must be large enough to fill a 10 × power field.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g06c.jpeg" height="1355" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma that underwent dedifferentiation. <b>(a)</b> CT scan obtained in 2003 shows a fatty mass (arrowheads) in the left perinephric space that was erroneously interpreted as a lipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan obtained 3 years later to evaluate urinary incontinence and increasing abdominal girth reveals a very large fatty mass that engulfs the left kidney and displaces the abdominal contents to the contralateral side. <b>(c)</b> A more cranial CT image shows multiple well-defined soft-tissue masses (arrowheads) embedded within the well-differentiated tumor. These masses are the hallmark of dedifferentiation. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the dedifferentiated liposarcoma clearly shows the central solid component (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a well-differentiated component immediately adjacent to a dedifferentiated component (<b>*</b>). The alipogenic dedifferentiated component can vary from low to high grade and must be large enough to fill a 10 × power field.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c06d.jpeg" height="1280" width="935" aria-labelledby="F6D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6d.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma that underwent dedifferentiation. <b>(a)</b> CT scan obtained in 2003 shows a fatty mass (arrowheads) in the left perinephric space that was erroneously interpreted as a lipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan obtained 3 years later to evaluate urinary incontinence and increasing abdominal girth reveals a very large fatty mass that engulfs the left kidney and displaces the abdominal contents to the contralateral side. <b>(c)</b> A more cranial CT image shows multiple well-defined soft-tissue masses (arrowheads) embedded within the well-differentiated tumor. These masses are the hallmark of dedifferentiation. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the dedifferentiated liposarcoma clearly shows the central solid component (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a well-differentiated component immediately adjacent to a dedifferentiated component (<b>*</b>). The alipogenic dedifferentiated component can vary from low to high grade and must be large enough to fill a 10 × power field.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F6D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c06e.jpeg" height="956" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F6E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6e.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma that underwent dedifferentiation. <b>(a)</b> CT scan obtained in 2003 shows a fatty mass (arrowheads) in the left perinephric space that was erroneously interpreted as a lipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan obtained 3 years later to evaluate urinary incontinence and increasing abdominal girth reveals a very large fatty mass that engulfs the left kidney and displaces the abdominal contents to the contralateral side. <b>(c)</b> A more cranial CT image shows multiple well-defined soft-tissue masses (arrowheads) embedded within the well-differentiated tumor. These masses are the hallmark of dedifferentiation. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the dedifferentiated liposarcoma clearly shows the central solid component (arrowheads). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a well-differentiated component immediately adjacent to a dedifferentiated component (<b>*</b>). The alipogenic dedifferentiated component can vary from low to high grade and must be large enough to fill a 10 × power field.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F6E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g07a.jpeg" height="1178" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a large left retroperitoneal fat-attenuation mass with a few internal septations (arrowhead) and fibrous strands. (Note how similar this lesion is to the mass in <a href="#F2A">Fig 2</a>.) <b>(b)</b> Preoperative coronal T1-weighted MR image facilitates surgical planning by depicting the femoral nerve within the center of the mass (arrowhead). The nerve was preserved during resection. <b>(c)</b> Image obtained during CT-guided biopsy demonstrates how needle path selection should traverse as few compartments as possible. Biopsy was used to confirm the diagnosis in anticipation of preoperative radiation therapy. <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H-E stain) shows the widened septa and atypical lipocytes (arrowheads), within both the septa and fatty lobules, findings characteristic of well-differentiated liposarcoma. A hyperchromatic enlarged lipocyte nucleus is depicted in the inset.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g07b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1696" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a large left retroperitoneal fat-attenuation mass with a few internal septations (arrowhead) and fibrous strands. (Note how similar this lesion is to the mass in <a href="#F2A">Fig 2</a>.) <b>(b)</b> Preoperative coronal T1-weighted MR image facilitates surgical planning by depicting the femoral nerve within the center of the mass (arrowhead). The nerve was preserved during resection. <b>(c)</b> Image obtained during CT-guided biopsy demonstrates how needle path selection should traverse as few compartments as possible. Biopsy was used to confirm the diagnosis in anticipation of preoperative radiation therapy. <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H-E stain) shows the widened septa and atypical lipocytes (arrowheads), within both the septa and fatty lobules, findings characteristic of well-differentiated liposarcoma. A hyperchromatic enlarged lipocyte nucleus is depicted in the inset.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g07c.jpeg" height="1178" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7c.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a large left retroperitoneal fat-attenuation mass with a few internal septations (arrowhead) and fibrous strands. (Note how similar this lesion is to the mass in <a href="#F2A">Fig 2</a>.) <b>(b)</b> Preoperative coronal T1-weighted MR image facilitates surgical planning by depicting the femoral nerve within the center of the mass (arrowhead). The nerve was preserved during resection. <b>(c)</b> Image obtained during CT-guided biopsy demonstrates how needle path selection should traverse as few compartments as possible. Biopsy was used to confirm the diagnosis in anticipation of preoperative radiation therapy. <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H-E stain) shows the widened septa and atypical lipocytes (arrowheads), within both the septa and fatty lobules, findings characteristic of well-differentiated liposarcoma. A hyperchromatic enlarged lipocyte nucleus is depicted in the inset.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F7C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c07d.jpeg" height="857" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F7D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7d.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a large left retroperitoneal fat-attenuation mass with a few internal septations (arrowhead) and fibrous strands. (Note how similar this lesion is to the mass in <a href="#F2A">Fig 2</a>.) <b>(b)</b> Preoperative coronal T1-weighted MR image facilitates surgical planning by depicting the femoral nerve within the center of the mass (arrowhead). The nerve was preserved during resection. <b>(c)</b> Image obtained during CT-guided biopsy demonstrates how needle path selection should traverse as few compartments as possible. Biopsy was used to confirm the diagnosis in anticipation of preoperative radiation therapy. <b>(d)</b> Low-power photomicrograph (original magnification, × 100; H-E stain) shows the widened septa and atypical lipocytes (arrowheads), within both the septa and fatty lobules, findings characteristic of well-differentiated liposarcoma. A hyperchromatic enlarged lipocyte nucleus is depicted in the inset.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F7D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g08a.jpeg" height="1086" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Perirenal myxoid liposarcoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous soft-tissue mass (arrowheads) with subtle geographic areas of lower attenuation. <b>(b)</b> On a T2-weighted MR image, the lower-attenuation areas seen in <b>a</b> appear as bright myxoid matrix (which contains a high percentage of water). <b>(c, d)</b> Coronal MR images obtained after gadolinium injection show early rim enhancement (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) with more homogeneous enhancement (<b>*</b>) in a later phase. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a fully solid lesion. The T2 bright signal can be misinterpreted as fluid, which is why these areas are labeled “pseudocystic.” <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows the unusual features of this tumor, which is more cellular and focally mimics myxofibrosarcoma (myxoid malignant fibrous histiocytoma) but clearly has myxoid change (<b>*</b>), delicate plexiform vessels, monovacuolated to bivacuolated lipoblasts, and stromal round cells. Inset demonstrates myxoid change, delicate vasculature, stromal round cells, and a bivacuolated lipoblast (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g08b.jpeg" height="1086" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Perirenal myxoid liposarcoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous soft-tissue mass (arrowheads) with subtle geographic areas of lower attenuation. <b>(b)</b> On a T2-weighted MR image, the lower-attenuation areas seen in <b>a</b> appear as bright myxoid matrix (which contains a high percentage of water). <b>(c, d)</b> Coronal MR images obtained after gadolinium injection show early rim enhancement (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) with more homogeneous enhancement (<b>*</b>) in a later phase. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a fully solid lesion. The T2 bright signal can be misinterpreted as fluid, which is why these areas are labeled “pseudocystic.” <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows the unusual features of this tumor, which is more cellular and focally mimics myxofibrosarcoma (myxoid malignant fibrous histiocytoma) but clearly has myxoid change (<b>*</b>), delicate plexiform vessels, monovacuolated to bivacuolated lipoblasts, and stromal round cells. Inset demonstrates myxoid change, delicate vasculature, stromal round cells, and a bivacuolated lipoblast (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g08c.jpeg" height="1098" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8c.</b>  Perirenal myxoid liposarcoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous soft-tissue mass (arrowheads) with subtle geographic areas of lower attenuation. <b>(b)</b> On a T2-weighted MR image, the lower-attenuation areas seen in <b>a</b> appear as bright myxoid matrix (which contains a high percentage of water). <b>(c, d)</b> Coronal MR images obtained after gadolinium injection show early rim enhancement (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) with more homogeneous enhancement (<b>*</b>) in a later phase. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a fully solid lesion. The T2 bright signal can be misinterpreted as fluid, which is why these areas are labeled “pseudocystic.” <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows the unusual features of this tumor, which is more cellular and focally mimics myxofibrosarcoma (myxoid malignant fibrous histiocytoma) but clearly has myxoid change (<b>*</b>), delicate plexiform vessels, monovacuolated to bivacuolated lipoblasts, and stromal round cells. Inset demonstrates myxoid change, delicate vasculature, stromal round cells, and a bivacuolated lipoblast (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F8C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g08d.jpeg" height="1100" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8d.</b>  Perirenal myxoid liposarcoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous soft-tissue mass (arrowheads) with subtle geographic areas of lower attenuation. <b>(b)</b> On a T2-weighted MR image, the lower-attenuation areas seen in <b>a</b> appear as bright myxoid matrix (which contains a high percentage of water). <b>(c, d)</b> Coronal MR images obtained after gadolinium injection show early rim enhancement (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) with more homogeneous enhancement (<b>*</b>) in a later phase. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a fully solid lesion. The T2 bright signal can be misinterpreted as fluid, which is why these areas are labeled “pseudocystic.” <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows the unusual features of this tumor, which is more cellular and focally mimics myxofibrosarcoma (myxoid malignant fibrous histiocytoma) but clearly has myxoid change (<b>*</b>), delicate plexiform vessels, monovacuolated to bivacuolated lipoblasts, and stromal round cells. Inset demonstrates myxoid change, delicate vasculature, stromal round cells, and a bivacuolated lipoblast (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F8D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure><