er-attenuation areas seen in <b>a</b> appear as bright myxoid matrix (which contains a high percentage of water). <b>(c, d)</b> Coronal MR images obtained after gadolinium injection show early rim enhancement (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) with more homogeneous enhancement (<b>*</b>) in a later phase. <b>(e)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows a fully solid lesion. The T2 bright signal can be misinterpreted as fluid, which is why these areas are labeled “pseudocystic.” <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows the unusual features of this tumor, which is more cellular and focally mimics myxofibrosarcoma (myxoid malignant fibrous histiocytoma) but clearly has myxoid change (<b>*</b>), delicate plexiform vessels, monovacuolated to bivacuolated lipoblasts, and stromal round cells. Inset demonstrates myxoid change, delicate vasculature, stromal round cells, and a bivacuolated lipoblast (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F8F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g09a.jpeg" height="1692" width="1498" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Pleomorphic liposarcoma in a 44-year-old man with crampy pain for 3 months. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a nonspecific solid-appearing mass (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous, peripherally enhancing soft-tissue mass with no calcifications. <b>(c)</b> On the T1-weighted MR image, no fat is seen within the lesion. <b>(d)</b> Contrast material–enhanced MR image depicts the enhancing periphery (arrowheads) and central necrotic core (<b>*</b>) that are characteristic of this tumor. <b>(e)</b> Photograph reveals the necrotic, liquefied center. <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows areas of malignant fibrous histiocytoma–like spindle cell sarcoma punctuated by bizarre, large lipoblasts (inset) with hyperchromatic enlarged nuclei that are scalloped by clear cytoplasmic vacuoles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g09b.jpeg" height="1311" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Pleomorphic liposarcoma in a 44-year-old man with crampy pain for 3 months. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a nonspecific solid-appearing mass (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous, peripherally enhancing soft-tissue mass with no calcifications. <b>(c)</b> On the T1-weighted MR image, no fat is seen within the lesion. <b>(d)</b> Contrast material–enhanced MR image depicts the enhancing periphery (arrowheads) and central necrotic core (<b>*</b>) that are characteristic of this tumor. <b>(e)</b> Photograph reveals the necrotic, liquefied center. <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows areas of malignant fibrous histiocytoma–like spindle cell sarcoma punctuated by bizarre, large lipoblasts (inset) with hyperchromatic enlarged nuclei that are scalloped by clear cytoplasmic vacuoles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g09c.jpeg" height="1318" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9c.</b>  Pleomorphic liposarcoma in a 44-year-old man with crampy pain for 3 months. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a nonspecific solid-appearing mass (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous, peripherally enhancing soft-tissue mass with no calcifications. <b>(c)</b> On the T1-weighted MR image, no fat is seen within the lesion. <b>(d)</b> Contrast material–enhanced MR image depicts the enhancing periphery (arrowheads) and central necrotic core (<b>*</b>) that are characteristic of this tumor. <b>(e)</b> Photograph reveals the necrotic, liquefied center. <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows areas of malignant fibrous histiocytoma–like spindle cell sarcoma punctuated by bizarre, large lipoblasts (inset) with hyperchromatic enlarged nuclei that are scalloped by clear cytoplasmic vacuoles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F9C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g09d.jpeg" height="1710" width="1515" aria-labelledby="F9D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9d.</b>  Pleomorphic liposarcoma in a 44-year-old man with crampy pain for 3 months. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a nonspecific solid-appearing mass (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous, peripherally enhancing soft-tissue mass with no calcifications. <b>(c)</b> On the T1-weighted MR image, no fat is seen within the lesion. <b>(d)</b> Contrast material–enhanced MR image depicts the enhancing periphery (arrowheads) and central necrotic core (<b>*</b>) that are characteristic of this tumor. <b>(e)</b> Photograph reveals the necrotic, liquefied center. <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows areas of malignant fibrous histiocytoma–like spindle cell sarcoma punctuated by bizarre, large lipoblasts (inset) with hyperchromatic enlarged nuclei that are scalloped by clear cytoplasmic vacuoles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F9D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c09e.jpeg" height="1016" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9e.</b>  Pleomorphic liposarcoma in a 44-year-old man with crampy pain for 3 months. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a nonspecific solid-appearing mass (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous, peripherally enhancing soft-tissue mass with no calcifications. <b>(c)</b> On the T1-weighted MR image, no fat is seen within the lesion. <b>(d)</b> Contrast material–enhanced MR image depicts the enhancing periphery (arrowheads) and central necrotic core (<b>*</b>) that are characteristic of this tumor. <b>(e)</b> Photograph reveals the necrotic, liquefied center. <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows areas of malignant fibrous histiocytoma–like spindle cell sarcoma punctuated by bizarre, large lipoblasts (inset) with hyperchromatic enlarged nuclei that are scalloped by clear cytoplasmic vacuoles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F9E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c09f.jpeg" height="753" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9f.</b>  Pleomorphic liposarcoma in a 44-year-old man with crampy pain for 3 months. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a nonspecific solid-appearing mass (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows a heterogeneous, peripherally enhancing soft-tissue mass with no calcifications. <b>(c)</b> On the T1-weighted MR image, no fat is seen within the lesion. <b>(d)</b> Contrast material–enhanced MR image depicts the enhancing periphery (arrowheads) and central necrotic core (<b>*</b>) that are characteristic of this tumor. <b>(e)</b> Photograph reveals the necrotic, liquefied center. <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows areas of malignant fibrous histiocytoma–like spindle cell sarcoma punctuated by bizarre, large lipoblasts (inset) with hyperchromatic enlarged nuclei that are scalloped by clear cytoplasmic vacuoles.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F9F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g10a.jpeg" height="1288" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma with extensive nonfatty elements. <b>(a)</b> CT scan reveals a right perinephric mass with extensive fat and patchy indistinct areas of soft-tissue attenuation that correspond to myxoid deposits. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a well-differentiated liposarcoma with atypical lipocytes (arrow) and abundant myxoid change (<b>*</b>). <b>(c)</b> CT scan of a different patient shows a right perinephric mass (arrowheads) that has predominantly soft-tissue attenuation within a faint background of fat. The soft-tissue component is due to extensive inflammatory infiltrates. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) demonstrates a well-differentiated liposarcoma with abundant lymphocytes (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c10b.jpeg" height="890" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma with extensive nonfatty elements. <b>(a)</b> CT scan reveals a right perinephric mass with extensive fat and patchy indistinct areas of soft-tissue attenuation that correspond to myxoid deposits. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a well-differentiated liposarcoma with atypical lipocytes (arrow) and abundant myxoid change (<b>*</b>). <b>(c)</b> CT scan of a different patient shows a right perinephric mass (arrowheads) that has predominantly soft-tissue attenuation within a faint background of fat. The soft-tissue component is due to extensive inflammatory infiltrates. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) demonstrates a well-differentiated liposarcoma with abundant lymphocytes (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c10d.jpeg" height="737" width="1024" aria-labelledby="F10D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10d.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma with extensive nonfatty elements. <b>(a)</b> CT scan reveals a right perinephric mass with extensive fat and patchy indistinct areas of soft-tissue attenuation that correspond to myxoid deposits. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a well-differentiated liposarcoma with atypical lipocytes (arrow) and abundant myxoid change (<b>*</b>). <b>(c)</b> CT scan of a different patient shows a right perinephric mass (arrowheads) that has predominantly soft-tissue attenuation within a faint background of fat. The soft-tissue component is due to extensive inflammatory infiltrates. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) demonstrates a well-differentiated liposarcoma with abundant lymphocytes (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F10D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g10c.jpeg" height="1289" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Well-differentiated liposarcoma with extensive nonfatty elements. <b>(a)</b> CT scan reveals a right perinephric mass with extensive fat and patchy indistinct areas of soft-tissue attenuation that correspond to myxoid deposits. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a well-differentiated liposarcoma with atypical lipocytes (arrow) and abundant myxoid change (<b>*</b>). <b>(c)</b> CT scan of a different patient shows a right perinephric mass (arrowheads) that has predominantly soft-tissue attenuation within a faint background of fat. The soft-tissue component is due to extensive inflammatory infiltrates. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) demonstrates a well-differentiated liposarcoma with abundant lymphocytes (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g11a.jpeg" height="1529" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Hibernoma in a 39-year-old man with a palpable mass in the buttocks. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT scan reveals a bilobed fatty mass (arrowheads) that extends through the right sciatic foramen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image reveals a rim of fluid attenuation (arrows) around the periphery of the mass that correlates with myxoid matrix, which is occasionally identified in hibernomas. <b>(c)</b> Another axial image shows large surface vessels (arrows), which are a common feature and are believed to partially explain the palpable warmth associated with hibernomas. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×200; H-E stain) shows the brown-fat eosinophilic cells, with central nuclei, small nucleoli, and multiple fine, small cytoplasmic vacuoles that do not scallop the nucleus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g11b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Hibernoma in a 39-year-old man with a palpable mass in the buttocks. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT scan reveals a bilobed fatty mass (arrowheads) that extends through the right sciatic foramen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image reveals a rim of fluid attenuation (arrows) around the periphery of the mass that correlates with myxoid matrix, which is occasionally identified in hibernomas. <b>(c)</b> Another axial image shows large surface vessels (arrows), which are a common feature and are believed to partially explain the palpable warmth associated with hibernomas. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×200; H-E stain) shows the brown-fat eosinophilic cells, with central nuclei, small nucleoli, and multiple fine, small cytoplasmic vacuoles that do not scallop the nucleus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g11c.jpeg" height="1246" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11c.</b>  Hibernoma in a 39-year-old man with a palpable mass in the buttocks. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT scan reveals a bilobed fatty mass (arrowheads) that extends through the right sciatic foramen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image reveals a rim of fluid attenuation (arrows) around the periphery of the mass that correlates with myxoid matrix, which is occasionally identified in hibernomas. <b>(c)</b> Another axial image shows large surface vessels (arrows), which are a common feature and are believed to partially explain the palpable warmth associated with hibernomas. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×200; H-E stain) shows the brown-fat eosinophilic cells, with central nuclei, small nucleoli, and multiple fine, small cytoplasmic vacuoles that do not scallop the nucleus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F11C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c11d.jpeg" height="858" width="1216" aria-labelledby="F11D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11d.</b>  Hibernoma in a 39-year-old man with a palpable mass in the buttocks. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT scan reveals a bilobed fatty mass (arrowheads) that extends through the right sciatic foramen. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image reveals a rim of fluid attenuation (arrows) around the periphery of the mass that correlates with myxoid matrix, which is occasionally identified in hibernomas. <b>(c)</b> Another axial image shows large surface vessels (arrows), which are a common feature and are believed to partially explain the palpable warmth associated with hibernomas. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×200; H-E stain) shows the brown-fat eosinophilic cells, with central nuclei, small nucleoli, and multiple fine, small cytoplasmic vacuoles that do not scallop the nucleus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F11D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g12a.jpeg" height="1388" width="1512" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Teratoma in a 4-month-old infant with a 2-week history of abdominal distention. <b>(a)</b> Abdominal radiograph reveals a large mass (arrowheads) with geographic areas of lucency from fat. Calcifications are best seen in the right upper quadrant (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows the fat-attenuation mass with multiple calcifications (black <b>*</b>) and fluid (white <b>*</b>). The combination of these three elements is highly specific for teratoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g12b.jpeg" height="1346" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Teratoma in a 4-month-old infant with a 2-week history of abdominal distention. <b>(a)</b> Abdominal radiograph reveals a large mass (arrowheads) with geographic areas of lucency from fat. Calcifications are best seen in the right upper quadrant (arrow). <b>(b)</b> CT scan shows the fat-attenuation mass with multiple calcifications (black <b>*</b>) and fluid (white <b>*</b>). The combination of these three elements is highly specific for teratoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g13a.jpeg" height="1433" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Teratoma in a 30-year-old woman with a 3-year history of increasing abdominal girth and early satiety. <b>(a)</b> US image demonstrates a complex mass with round, solid components (<b>*</b>), some of which create shadowing. <b>(b, c)</b> CT scans show fat (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), soft tissue (white <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), and calcification (black <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), with more solid-appearing spherical elements (arrowheads in <b>c</b>) that correlate well with the US findings. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the lobulated mass shows that it contains hair and cheeselike sebaceous material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g13b.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Teratoma in a 30-year-old woman with a 3-year history of increasing abdominal girth and early satiety. <b>(a)</b> US image demonstrates a complex mass with round, solid components (<b>*</b>), some of which create shadowing. <b>(b, c)</b> CT scans show fat (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), soft tissue (white <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), and calcification (black <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), with more solid-appearing spherical elements (arrowheads in <b>c</b>) that correlate well with the US findings. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the lobulated mass shows that it contains hair and cheeselike sebaceous material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g13c.jpeg" height="1295" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13c.</b>  Teratoma in a 30-year-old woman with a 3-year history of increasing abdominal girth and early satiety. <b>(a)</b> US image demonstrates a complex mass with round, solid components (<b>*</b>), some of which create shadowing. <b>(b, c)</b> CT scans show fat (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), soft tissue (white <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), and calcification (black <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), with more solid-appearing spherical elements (arrowheads in <b>c</b>) that correlate well with the US findings. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the lobulated mass shows that it contains hair and cheeselike sebaceous material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F13C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c13d.jpeg" height="1011" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F13D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13d.</b>  Teratoma in a 30-year-old woman with a 3-year history of increasing abdominal girth and early satiety. <b>(a)</b> US image demonstrates a complex mass with round, solid components (<b>*</b>), some of which create shadowing. <b>(b, c)</b> CT scans show fat (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), soft tissue (white <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), and calcification (black <b>*</b> in <b>b</b>), with more solid-appearing spherical elements (arrowheads in <b>c</b>) that correlate well with the US findings. <b>(d)</b> Photograph of the lobulated mass shows that it contains hair and cheeselike sebaceous material.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F13D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g14a.jpeg" height="1332" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Myelolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows an adrenal lesion (arrowhead) that contains fat, a finding characteristic of myelolipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan from another case shows an extraadrenal myelolipoma (arrowhead) in the right retroperitoneum that mimics a liposarcoma. <b>(c, d)</b> CT scans of two different patients show a myelolipoma (<b>*</b>) in the presacral space (a common location for extraadrenal disease). The lesions demonstrate the extreme variability in fat and nonfatty components. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a mixture of mature fat and marrow elements, including large multinucleated, pink cytoplasm megakaryocytes (arrow), which are platelet cell precursors. <b>*</b> = adrenal gland.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g14b.jpeg" height="1348" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14b.</b>  Myelolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows an adrenal lesion (arrowhead) that contains fat, a finding characteristic of myelolipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan from another case shows an extraadrenal myelolipoma (arrowhead) in the right retroperitoneum that mimics a liposarcoma. <b>(c, d)</b> CT scans of two different patients show a myelolipoma (<b>*</b>) in the presacral space (a common location for extraadrenal disease). The lesions demonstrate the extreme variability in fat and nonfatty components. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a mixture of mature fat and marrow elements, including large multinucleated, pink cytoplasm megakaryocytes (arrow), which are platelet cell precursors. <b>*</b> = adrenal gland.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F14B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g14c.jpeg" height="1348" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14c.</b>  Myelolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows an adrenal lesion (arrowhead) that contains fat, a finding characteristic of myelolipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan from another case shows an extraadrenal myelolipoma (arrowhead) in the right retroperitoneum that mimics a liposarcoma. <b>(c, d)</b> CT scans of two different patients show a myelolipoma (<b>*</b>) in the presacral space (a common location for extraadrenal disease). The lesions demonstrate the extreme variability in fat and nonfatty components. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a mixture of mature fat and marrow elements, including large multinucleated, pink cytoplasm megakaryocytes (arrow), which are platelet cell precursors. <b>*</b> = adrenal gland.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F14C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g14d.jpeg" height="1284" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14d.</b>  Myelolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows an adrenal lesion (arrowhead) that contains fat, a finding characteristic of myelolipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan from another case shows an extraadrenal myelolipoma (arrowhead) in the right retroperitoneum that mimics a liposarcoma. <b>(c, d)</b> CT scans of two different patients show a myelolipoma (<b>*</b>) in the presacral space (a common location for extraadrenal disease). The lesions demonstrate the extreme variability in fat and nonfatty components. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a mixture of mature fat and marrow elements, including large multinucleated, pink cytoplasm megakaryocytes (arrow), which are platelet cell precursors. <b>*</b> = adrenal gland.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F14D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c14e.jpeg" height="932" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F14E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14e.</b>  Myelolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows an adrenal lesion (arrowhead) that contains fat, a finding characteristic of myelolipoma. <b>(b)</b> CT scan from another case shows an extraadrenal myelolipoma (arrowhead) in the right retroperitoneum that mimics a liposarcoma. <b>(c, d)</b> CT scans of two different patients show a myelolipoma (<b>*</b>) in the presacral space (a common location for extraadrenal disease). The lesions demonstrate the extreme variability in fat and nonfatty components. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 200; H-E stain) shows a mixture of mature fat and marrow elements, including large multinucleated, pink cytoplasm megakaryocytes (arrow), which are platelet cell precursors. <b>*</b> = adrenal gland.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F14E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g15a.jpeg" height="1040" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15a.</b>  Angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a fat-containing mass that is clearly exophytic from the kidney. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT scans show an angiomyolipoma in a 45-year-old man who presented with a palpable left-sided mass and varicocele. The case was originally referred to the AFIP as a liposarcoma. However, the presence of large internal vessels (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and a renal notch (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) both strongly favor the diagnosis of angiomyolipoma rather than liposarcoma. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; H-E stain) demonstrates a triphasic tumor with vessels, immature epithelioid smooth muscle, and fat. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; HMB45 immunostain) of the epithelioid smooth muscle component shows that the tumor is myomelanocytic (brown stain) and is positive for these melanoma markers as well as desmin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F15A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g15b.jpeg" height="1584" width="1504" aria-labelledby="F15B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15b.</b>  Angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a fat-containing mass that is clearly exophytic from the kidney. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT scans show an angiomyolipoma in a 45-year-old man who presented with a palpable left-sided mass and varicocele. The case was originally referred to the AFIP as a liposarcoma. However, the presence of large internal vessels (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and a renal notch (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) both strongly favor the diagnosis of angiomyolipoma rather than liposarcoma. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; H-E stain) demonstrates a triphasic tumor with vessels, immature epithelioid smooth muscle, and fat. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; HMB45 immunostain) of the epithelioid smooth muscle component shows that the tumor is myomelanocytic (brown stain) and is positive for these melanoma markers as well as desmin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F15B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g15c.jpeg" height="1289" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15c.</b>  Angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a fat-containing mass that is clearly exophytic from the kidney. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT scans show an angiomyolipoma in a 45-year-old man who presented with a palpable left-sided mass and varicocele. The case was originally referred to the AFIP as a liposarcoma. However, the presence of large internal vessels (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and a renal notch (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) both strongly favor the diagnosis of angiomyolipoma rather than liposarcoma. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; H-E stain) demonstrates a triphasic tumor with vessels, immature epithelioid smooth muscle, and fat. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; HMB45 immunostain) of the epithelioid smooth muscle component shows that the tumor is myomelanocytic (brown stain) and is positive for these melanoma markers as well as desmin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F15C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c15d.jpeg" height="890" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15d.</b>  Angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a fat-containing mass that is clearly exophytic from the kidney. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT scans show an angiomyolipoma in a 45-year-old man who presented with a palpable left-sided mass and varicocele. The case was originally referred to the AFIP as a liposarcoma. However, the presence of large internal vessels (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and a renal notch (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) both strongly favor the diagnosis of angiomyolipoma rather than liposarcoma. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; H-E stain) demonstrates a triphasic tumor with vessels, immature epithelioid smooth muscle, and fat. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; HMB45 immunostain) of the epithelioid smooth muscle component shows that the tumor is myomelanocytic (brown stain) and is positive for these melanoma markers as well as desmin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F15D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c15e.jpeg" height="922" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15e.</b>  Angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a fat-containing mass that is clearly exophytic from the kidney. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT scans show an angiomyolipoma in a 45-year-old man who presented with a palpable left-sided mass and varicocele. The case was originally referred to the AFIP as a liposarcoma. However, the presence of large internal vessels (arrowheads in <b>b</b>) and a renal notch (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) both strongly favor the diagnosis of angiomyolipoma rather than liposarcoma. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; H-E stain) demonstrates a triphasic tumor with vessels, immature epithelioid smooth muscle, and fat. <b>(e)</b> Photomicrograph (original magnification, × 400; HMB45 immunostain) of the epithelioid smooth muscle component shows that the tumor is myomelanocytic (brown stain) and is positive for these melanoma markers as well as desmin.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F15E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g16a.jpeg" height="1315" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16a.</b>  Vascular complications of angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan demonstrates a hematoma filling the right perinephric space (arrowheads) from the anterior exophytic angiomyolipoma. <b>(b)</b> Vascular phase CT scan through an aneurysm shows the focally hyperenhancing lesion (arrowhead), which parallels the aorta due to aneurysm formation. <b>(c)</b> Angiogram obtained before preoperative embolization shows the aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs (original magnification, × 150; Movat stain) show a normal vessel, in which the black elastic lamina (arrowhead) is readily apparent (left image), and an angiomyolipoma, in which the lamina is notably absent (right image). Absence of the lamina weakens the vessel, predisposing it to aneurysm formation and hemorrhage. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#R94" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R94">94</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F16A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g16b.jpeg" height="1362" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16b.</b>  Vascular complications of angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan demonstrates a hematoma filling the right perinephric space (arrowheads) from the anterior exophytic angiomyolipoma. <b>(b)</b> Vascular phase CT scan through an aneurysm shows the focally hyperenhancing lesion (arrowhead), which parallels the aorta due to aneurysm formation. <b>(c)</b> Angiogram obtained before preoperative embolization shows the aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs (original magnification, × 150; Movat stain) show a normal vessel, in which the black elastic lamina (arrowhead) is readily apparent (left image), and an angiomyolipoma, in which the lamina is notably absent (right image). Absence of the lamina weakens the vessel, predisposing it to aneurysm formation and hemorrhage. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#R94" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R94">94</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F16B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29g16c.jpeg" height="1118" width="1475" aria-labelledby="F16C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16c.</b>  Vascular complications of angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan demonstrates a hematoma filling the right perinephric space (arrowheads) from the anterior exophytic angiomyolipoma. <b>(b)</b> Vascular phase CT scan through an aneurysm shows the focally hyperenhancing lesion (arrowhead), which parallels the aorta due to aneurysm formation. <b>(c)</b> Angiogram obtained before preoperative embolization shows the aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs (original magnification, × 150; Movat stain) show a normal vessel, in which the black elastic lamina (arrowhead) is readily apparent (left image), and an angiomyolipoma, in which the lamina is notably absent (right image). Absence of the lamina weakens the vessel, predisposing it to aneurysm formation and hemorrhage. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#R94" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R94">94</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F16C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291085203/asset/images/g09ja29c16d.jpeg" height="860" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F16D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16d.</b>  Vascular complications of angiomyolipoma. <b>(a)</b> CT scan demonstrates a hematoma filling the right perinephric space (arrowheads) from the anterior exophytic angiomyolipoma. <b>(b)</b> Vascular phase CT scan through an aneurysm shows the focally hyperenhancing lesion (arrowhead), which parallels the aorta due to aneurysm formation. <b>(c)</b> Angiogram obtained before preoperative embolization shows the aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs (original magnification, × 150; Movat stain) show a normal vessel, in which the black elastic lamina (arrowhead) is readily apparent (left image), and an angiomyolipoma, in which the lamina is notably absent (right image). Absence of the lamina weakens the vessel, predisposing it to aneurysm formation and hemorrhage. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#R94" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R94">94</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291085203&amp;id=F16D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Engels</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">EP</span></span>. Sigmoid colon and urinary bladder in high fixation: roentgen changes simulating pelvic tumor. <em>Radiology</em>1959; 72: 419–422.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/72.3.419">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/13634406/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Radiology&amp;publication_year=1959&amp;pages=419&amp;doi=10.1148%2F72.3.419&amp;pmid=13634406">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="cita