le="paragraph">The clinical, pathologic, and radiologic features of and treatment approaches for fat-containing lesions of the retroperitoneum are reviewed, with emphasis on radiologic-pathologic correlation.</div></section></section><section id="tab-contributors" role="tabpanel"><h3>Authors</h3><section class="core-authors"><h4>Affiliations</h4><div id="con1" property="author" typeof="Person"><div class="heading"><span property="givenName">William D.</span> <span property="familyName">Craig</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">CDR, MC, USN</span></div><div class="content"><div class="affiliations"><div property="affiliation" typeof="Organization"><span property="name">From the Departments of Radiologic Pathology (W.D.C.), Orthopaedic and Soft Tissue Pathology (J.C.F.S.), and Genitourinary Pathology (J.H.B.), Armed Forces Institute of Pathology, 6825 16th St NW, Washington, DC 20306-6000; Departments of Radiology Nuclear Medicine (W.D.C.) and Surgery (L.R.H.), Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences, Bethesda, Md; Department of Surgical Oncology, National Naval Medical Center, Bethesda, Md (L.R.H.); and Department of Radiology, Hospital de la Santa Creu i Sant Pau, Barcelona, Spain (R.G.). Received September 2, 2008; revision requested September 24; revision received October 15; accepted October 17. All authors have no financial relationships to disclose.</span></div></div><div class="core-author-link"><a href="/authored-by/Craig/William+D" rel="nofollow">View all articles by this author</a></div></div></div><div id="con2" property="author" typeof="Person"><div class="heading"><span property="givenName">Julie C.</span> <span property="familyName">Fanburg-Smith</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></div><div class="content"><div class="affiliations"><div property="affiliation" typeof="Organization"><span property="name">From the Departments of Radiologic Pathology (W.D.C.), Orthopaedic and Soft Tissue Pathology (J.C.F.S.), and Genitourin